[[File:Olwyn, Nathan, Pam and 03W March 11 2015 0330Z.png|thumb|right|300px|Tropical cyclones [[2014–15 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Olwyn|Olwyn]] ''(left)'', [[2014–15 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Nathan|Nathan]] ''(center)'', [[Tropical Storm Bavi (2015)|Bavi]] ''(top right)'', and [[Cyclone Pam|Pam]] ''(bottom right)'' on March&nbsp;11, 2015. Bavi and Pam developed simultaneously as a result of a westerly wind burst.<ref name="NOAAMarch2015"/>]] A '''westerly wind burst''' is a phenomenon commonly associated with [[El Niño]] events whereby the typical east-to-west [[trade winds]] across the [[equator]]ial Pacific shift to west-to-east. A westerly wind burst is defined by Harrison and Vecchi (1997) as sustained winds of {{convert|25|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} over a period of 5–20&nbsp;days.<ref name="Eisenman2005"/> However, no concrete definition has been determined, with Tziperman and Yu (2007) defining them as having winds of {{convert|14|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and lasting "at least a few days".<ref name="Tziperman2007">{{cite journal|author1=Eli Tziperman |author2=Lisan Yu |lastauthoramp=yes |journal=Journal of Climate|publisher=American Meteorological Society|volume=20|issue=12|date=October 2007|accessdate=January 9, 2016|title=Quantifying the Dependence of Westerly Wind Bursts on the Large-Scale Tropical Pacific SST|format=PDF|pages=2,760–2,768|doi=10.1175/JCLI4138a.1|url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/pdf/10.1175/JCLI4138a.1|bibcode = 2007JCli...20.2760T }}</ref> On average, three of these events take place each year, but are significantly more common during El Niño years. They have been linked to various [[Mesoscale meteorology|mesoscale]] phenomena, including [[tropical cyclones]], mid-latitude cold surges, and the [[Madden–Julian oscillation]]. Their connection with [[Kelvin wave]]s also indicate a connection with the onset of El Niño events, with every major occurrence since the 1950s featuring a westerly wind burst upon their onset.<ref name="Eisenman2005">{{cite journal|author1=Ian Eisenman |author2=Lisan Yu |author3=Eli Tziperman |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Journal of Climate|publisher=American Meteorological Society|date=December 2005|accessdate=January 9, 2016|title=Westerly Wind Bursts: ENSO’s Tail Rather than the Dog?|url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/pdf/10.1175/JCLI3588.1|format=PDF|volume=18|issue=24|doi=10.1175/JCLI3588.1|pages=5,224–5,238|bibcode = 2005JCli...18.5224E }}</ref>
Recent studies, including Yu et al. (2003), have indicated some correlation between westerly wind bursts and the [[El Niño–Southern Oscillation]] (ENSO). These events occur more frequently when the equatorial Pacific warm pool is extended by ENSO events. A significant relationship exists between the frequency of westerly wind bursts and the central equatorial Pacific [[sea surface temperature]]s, with events commonly taking place when {{convert|29|C|F|abbr=on}} temperatures were present. The wind bursts also traveled along with the warm pool, propagating west to east.<ref name="Eisenman2005"/>
A westerly wind burst event can often result in the formation of twin tropical cyclones in the Pacific, with events occurring once per year on average. These events spur counter-clockwise rotation in the [[Northern Hemisphere]] and clockwise rotation in the [[Southern Hemisphere]]—a key component of [[Low-pressure area|low pressure systems]].<ref name="NOAAMarch2015">{{cite web|author=Tom Di Liberto|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=January 9, 2016|title=Twin tropical cyclones in western Pacific |url=https://www.climate.gov/news-features/event-tracker/twin-tropical-cyclones-western-pacific}}</ref> For example, during July&nbsp;2015 [[Typhoon Chan-hom (2015)|Typhoon Chan-hom]] and [[2014–15 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Raquel|Tropical Cyclone Raquel]] developed simultaneously over the Northwestern and Southwestern Pacific, respectively, in conjunction with a westerly wind burst. This was also the only known instance of twin cyclones during July and attributed to the record strength of the [[2014–16 El Niño event]].<ref name="peu">{{cite journal|journal=Pacific ENSO Update|title=A Quarterly Bulletin of the Pacific El Nino-Southern Oscillation Applications Climate (PEAC) Center|date=July 30, 2015|volume=21|number=3|accessdate=January 9, 2016|url=http://www.weather.gov/media/peac/PEU/PEU_v21_n3.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> Another unusually strong wind burst led to the atypical formations of [[2015 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Depression Nine-C|Tropical Depression Nine-C]] and [[2016 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Pali|Tropical Storm Pali]] in late December&nbsp;2015 and early January&nbsp;2016, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bob Henson|publisher=Weather Underground|date=January 7, 2016|accessdate=January 9, 2016|title=Rare January Depression in Central Pacific; Atlantic Subtropical Storm Next Week?|url=http://www.wunderground.com/blog/JeffMasters/comment.html?entrynum=3218}}</ref> Similarly, the formation of twin cyclones along the equatorial Pacific can spur the formation of a westerly wind burst and enhance El Niño events.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrea Thompson|publisher=Climate Central|date=March 13, 2015|accessdate=January 9, 2016|title=‘Twin’ Cyclones Could Jolt Weak El Nino|url=http://www.climatecentral.org/news/twin-cyclones-could-jolt-weak-el-nino-18775}}</ref> In May 2002, a strong westerly wind burst moved from west to east across the Indian Ocean, producing two separate sets of twin cyclones. It first led to the development of [[Cyclone Kesiny]] in the south-west Indian Ocean and a [[2002 Oman cyclone|storm]] that struck Oman, and later spawned [[2002 North Indian Ocean cyclone season#Deep Depression (02B)|a deep depression]] that struck Myanmar and [[2001–02 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Errol|Tropical Storm Errol]] to the southwest of [[Indonesia]].<ref name="mf">{{cite report|publisher=Météo-France|pages=64–75|title=2001–2002 South-West Indian Ocean Cyclone Season|accessdate=2012-10-23|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/archives/publications/saisons_cycloniques/index20012002.html}}</ref>
